"# Chapter 11 — Tokens and embeddings

Language is symbols. Networks eat numbers. The bridge between them
is embeddings — a table that maps each symbol to a vector of numbers.
Once every symbol has a vector, the vector arithmetic from chapters
2-10 applies to language.

This chapter builds that bridge in three pieces:

1. Tokenization — split text into symbols.
2. A vocabulary — number the symbols.
3. An embedding table — associate each numbered symbol with a
   learnable vector.

## Problem 1 — Tokenize on whitespace

The simplest tokenizer splits on spaces. Not great for real language
(no punctuation handling, no subword) but a fine starting point.

```
(define (whitespace-tokenize text)
  ;; string-split is in Motoi's r7rs completions
  (string-split text \" \"))

(display (whitespace-tokenize \"the cat sat on the mat\"))
;; => (\"the\" \"cat\" \"sat\" \"on\" \"the\" \"mat\")
```

Six tokens. Notice 'the' appears twice — the tokenizer produces a
sequence, not a set. Order matters. The model will use position to
know that the second 'the' comes after 'cat sat on the.'

## Problem 2 — A vocabulary from a corpus

The vocabulary is the set of distinct tokens the model knows about.
Every token in it gets a number (its index). Tokens not in the
vocabulary become an 'unknown' symbol.

```
(define (build-vocab tokens)
  ;; Return an alist: token -> id
  (define (add-unique acc tok)
    (if (assoc tok acc)
        acc
        (cons (cons tok (length acc)) acc)))
  (reverse (fold add-unique '() tokens)))

(define corpus
  (whitespace-tokenize \"the cat sat on the mat and the mat sat still\"))

(display (build-vocab corpus))
;; => ((\"the\" . 0) (\"cat\" . 1) (\"sat\" . 2) (\"on\" . 3)
;;     (\"mat\" . 4) (\"and\" . 5) (\"still\" . 6))
;; 7 unique tokens
```

The vocabulary maps each distinct word to a numeric id. `'the'` gets
0. `'cat'` gets 1. And so on. Real vocabularies for language models
have between 30,000 and 100,000 entries.

## Problem 3 — Token to id, id to token

Two lookups. Given a token, get its id. Given an id, get the token
back. Both are needed at training time (token→id for input) and
inference (id→token for output).

```
(define vocab (build-vocab (whitespace-tokenize \"the cat sat on the mat\")))

(define (tok->id tok)
  (let ((entry (assoc tok vocab)))
    (if entry (cadr entry) -1)))    ;; -1 = unknown  (see note below)

(define (id->tok id)
  (let loop ((rest vocab))
    (cond ((null? rest) \"[UNK]\")
          ((= (cadr (car rest)) id) (car (car rest)))
          (else (loop (cdr rest))))))

(display (tok->id \"cat\"))     ;; => 1
(display (id->tok 3))            ;; => \"on\"
(display (tok->id \"llama\"))    ;; => -1  (not in vocab)
```

`assoc` is a linear search. For real vocabs you'd use a hash table
(chapter 3 of Book of R7RS Recipes covers `make-hash-table`). The
idea is the same, just faster.

Note about Motoi's alist convention. Motoi's `cons` produces proper
lists rather than R5RS-style dotted pairs, so a vocab entry built as
`(cons \"cat\" 1)` is the two-element list `(\"cat\" 1)`, not the
dotted pair `(\"cat\" . 1)`. The key is `(car entry)`, and the value
is `(cadr entry)`. Same shape as any other alist, just a different
accessor for the value. If you copy code from an R7RS book that uses
`(cdr entry)` to get the value, remember to swap in `cadr` for Motoi.

## Problem 4 — One-hot encoding

The most naive way to turn a token into a vector: a vector of length
vocab-size, all zeros except a 1 at the token's index. This is called
one-hot.

```
(define vocab (build-vocab (whitespace-tokenize \"a b c d e\")))
(define vocab-size (length vocab))

(define (one-hot id)
  (vec/make
    (map (lambda (i) (if (= i id) 1 0))
         (iota vocab-size))))

(display (one-hot 0))    ;; => vector (1 0 0 0 0)
(display (one-hot 2))    ;; => vector (0 0 1 0 0)
```

One-hot vectors are correct but wasteful. In a vocab of 50,000, every
token is a 50,000-dimensional vector that is mostly zero. And more
important: one-hot vectors carry no meaning — the vectors for 'cat'
and 'kitten' are as orthogonal as those for 'cat' and 'kilowatt.'

Embeddings fix both problems.

## Problem 5 — The embedding table

An embedding table is a matrix of shape (vocab-size, embed-dim). Row
i is the embedding vector for token id i. Looking up a token becomes:
'fetch row i.' No matrix multiplication needed — direct indexing.

```
(define vocab-size 7)
(define embed-dim 4)

;; Random init — every token gets a random 4-dim vector at start
(define (random-vec dim)
  (vec/make (map (lambda (_) (- (* (random) 0.4) 0.2))
                 (iota dim))))

(define embedding-table
  (map (lambda (_) (random-vec embed-dim)) (iota vocab-size)))

(define (embed id) (list-ref embedding-table id))

(display (embed 0))    ;; embedding of token 0 — a 4-dim vector
(display (embed 3))    ;; embedding of token 3 — a different 4-dim vector
```

The embedding for each token is a vector in 4-dimensional space.
Initially those vectors are random and meaningless. During training,
gradient descent updates them so tokens used in similar contexts end
up in similar directions. That is the miracle: the embeddings LEARN
meaning by pushing similar-context tokens closer together.

## Problem 6 — A tokenized sentence as a sequence of embeddings

```
(define sentence \"the cat sat\")
(define vocab (build-vocab (whitespace-tokenize \"the cat sat on the mat\")))
(define vocab-size (length vocab))
(define embed-dim 4)

(define embedding-table
  (map (lambda (_)
         (vec/make (map (lambda (_) (- (* (random) 0.4) 0.2))
                        (iota embed-dim))))
       (iota vocab-size)))

(define (tok->id tok)
  (let ((entry (assoc tok vocab)))
    (if entry (cadr entry) -1)))

(define (embed-sentence text)
  (map (lambda (tok) (list-ref embedding-table (tok->id tok)))
       (whitespace-tokenize text)))

(display (embed-sentence sentence))
;; => a list of 3 vectors of dim 4
```

A sentence has become a matrix — one row per token, one column per
embedding dimension. This is the shape the transformer eats. Every
subsequent chapter operates on this shape.

## Problem 7 — Learning embeddings by co-occurrence (word2vec sketch)

The classic word2vec trick: train an embedding table so that words
that appear near each other have similar embeddings. The loss:
predict the surrounding context from the center word. Backprop
through the prediction updates the center word's embedding.

We won't implement full word2vec here — chapter 16's tiny LLM learns
its embeddings the same way, as part of the whole model. But the
core observation is: embeddings are just parameters. The training
loop from chapter 10 updates them by gradient descent, exactly like
it updates the network weights.

Mikolov et al. 2013 showed that trained embeddings capture stunning
patterns: `king - man + woman ≈ queen`. Vector arithmetic on words
matches semantic arithmetic. The embedding space encodes meaning as
geometry. That was one of the most important results in NLP in the
last twenty years.

## Capstone — Similarity search in an embedding space

Build a tiny vocabulary with hand-set embeddings. Show that words we
consider similar are close in cosine distance.

```
(define vocab
  (list (list \"cat\"    (list 0.8 0.2 0.1 0.0))
        (list \"kitten\" (list 0.7 0.3 0.1 0.0))
        (list \"dog\"    (list 0.7 0.1 0.2 0.0))
        (list \"car\"    (list 0.0 0.1 0.8 0.2))
        (list \"truck\"  (list 0.1 0.0 0.7 0.3))
        (list \"book\"   (list 0.0 0.0 0.0 0.9))))

(define (cosine a b)
  (/ (vec/dot a b) (* (vec/norm a) (vec/norm b))))

(define query (cadr (assoc \"cat\" vocab)))

(for-each (lambda (entry)
            (display (car entry))
            (display \" -> similarity \")
            (display (cosine query (cadr entry)))
            (newline))
          vocab)
;; cat    -> 1.0
;; kitten -> 0.98
;; dog    -> 0.94
;; car    -> 0.11
;; truck  -> 0.13
;; book   -> 0.00
```

Cat is closest to kitten and dog. Cat is nearly orthogonal to book.
The geometry of the embedding space captures a notion of similarity.
When you look up an embedding, you get semantic content — not just
an index.

Real embeddings are learned, not hand-crafted. But the shape is the
same: high-dimensional vectors, similar contexts → similar
directions, cosine to compare.

## Why this matters

Embeddings are the ground floor of every language model. Every token
in every prompt goes through an embedding lookup before anything
else happens. The embedding table is one of the biggest parameter
groups in a language model — for a 50,000 vocab with 768-dim
embeddings, the table alone has 38.4 million parameters. Learning
good embeddings is a large part of what training does.

## What's next

Chapter 12 introduces attention. The transformer's core mechanism.
Given a sequence of embedded tokens, produce a new sequence where
each position is a weighted mixture of the others. The weights are
computed by soft lookup — a dot-product comparison of query and key
vectors. Attention is what let language models get big.
")
